:: II. Two Currents
“I was twenty-one,” the old man says, lifting the tiny porcelain cup toward his lips, “and the world had suddenly become too small for me.” 
Bologna felt narrow, predictable, and carefully arranged, his future even more so, and so when the Venetian ambassador needed a young man to travel with 
him in 1679, Marsili accepted without hesitation. “Constantinople,” he says, and the word leaves his mouth less like a destination and more like a memory 
he still returns to when the room grows quiet enough. He lived there for months, learning fragments of Turkish, wandering through crowded streets and coffee 
houses where men played chess for hours without ever raising their voices, and it was there that he met a scholar named Husayn Efendi, who wrote about coffee 
with the seriousness other men reserved for religion or war. “He gave me his writings,” Marsili says softly. “He has been dead for many years, but I still read 
his words. In that way, he is not entirely gone.”
But it was not the city itself that fascinated him most. It was the Bosporus, the narrow strait dividing two worlds, where something impossible seemed 
to happen beneath the surface of the water. Fishermen had known about it for centuries: one current moved south across the surface while another, deeper 
current flowed north beneath it, the two waters moving against one another at the same time. People spoke about it, repeated theories, passed down stories, 
but no one had properly tested it. “So I did something very simple,” Marsili says, leaning forward slightly. “I lowered a bottle into the water and measured 
what returned.” The deeper water proved colder, saltier, and heavier than the surface above it, and from that small experiment he began to understand something 
larger—that the sea was not a single body moving as one, but layers upon layers of hidden motion, currents invisible from above yet shaping the entire world 
beneath.

A faint smile crosses his face. “I did not know then that I was making some of the first oceanographic observations in history. 
I was only twenty-one. I only knew that nobody else seemed willing to get their sleeves wet.”

