:: III. The Rába
“I tell this one badly,” the old man says after a long silence, his fingers resting against the empty porcelain cup as though he has forgotten it is there. 
“Every time I speak of it, something feels wrong, as though memory itself refuses to stay still long enough to become a proper story.” Still, he continues.
In 1681 he joined the army of the Holy Roman Emperor, not because he dreamed of glory but because he wanted to see the borderlands for himself, the violent 
edges where empires pressed against each other like grinding stone. “A library cannot show you that kind of world,” he says quietly. “A horse can.” Two years 
later, in 1683, while the Ottoman army marched toward Vienna, Marsili found himself far from the famous siege itself in a smaller battle along 
the river Rába in Hungary, a skirmish history barely remembers but one he never escaped in memory. What he recalls most is not strategy or 
heroism but confusion: dust thick enough to blind, shouting so close it no longer sounded human, the crushing weight of a horse collapsing onto him, 
and the freezing shock of river water against his side. “I remember thinking only one thing,” he says softly. “So this is how it ends. I was twenty-five years old.”

He explains that battle did not resemble paintings or songs; it was chaos so complete that survival often depended more on chance than skill. 
Men shouted in languages he barely understood, horses screamed louder than soldiers, and for moments at a time he could not even tell 
whether he was alive or dying. But he survived for one simple reason: the men who found him did not kill him. They were Crimean Tartar riders
fighting for the Ottoman forces, and even beneath blood and mud they recognized he was a gentleman. To them, a noble prisoner was valuable,
“a coin yet to be spent,” as Marsili calls it. One of the riders lifted his chin and examined his face carefully, not cruelly but with the detached attention 
of someone inspecting cloth in a market before deciding its worth, and in that moment Marsili understood something terrible—that count, scholar, 
and young nobleman from Bologna no longer meant anything. “On the banks of the Rába,” he says quietly, “I stopped being Marsili of Bologna and became merchandise.”

[[Ask what happened after his capture -> IV. The Coin Yet to Be Spent]]
[[Return to the objects on his desk -> Conversation]]


=========================================================================

:: IV. The Coin Yet to Be Spent
“It is a small word—sold,” the old man says quietly, staring into the last traces of coffee left inside his cup. “But spoken by the one who lived it, 
it becomes much larger.” After the battle at the Rába, the Crimean Tartars did not keep him long. He was wounded, feverish, and slowed them down, and 
so he was passed onward to men who traded in prisoners the same way others traded horses or cloth. Marsili explains that there was nothing dramatic 
about it—no auction blocks or shouted prices, only tents, quiet conversations, and hands exchanging money while he moved from one owner to another like an 
object whose value needed to be measured before use. “They did not hate me,” he says. “But they did not see me as human either. I was useful. That was enough.”

Still, among those memories, one detail remains strangely gentle. There was a woman who treated his wounds with hot water and wine, 
cleaning the infection without ever speaking a single word to him. Marsili admits he never learned her name, yet after all these years he still 
remembers her hands more clearly than many faces. “I think she saved my life,” he says softly, pausing longer than before. Eventually he was taken
into the household of the Pasha of Temesvar, who examined him the way a man might inspect an animal in a market before purchase. The pasha said something 
that made the others laugh, words Marsili only understood years later: this one will live. The old man exhales slowly after repeating it. “And he was right.
I did live. But the body never forgets what it once became.” For a moment he rubs absentmindedly at his wrist. “Even now,” he says quietly, 
“a stranger touching my arm unexpectedly can return me there for an instant.”

[[Ask what life under the Pasha was like -> V. Invisible Things]]
[[Return to the objects on his desk -> Conversation]]

============================================================

:: V. Invisible Things
“The Pasha of Temesvar made me a servant,” the old man says, “though the word itself is far too small for what it meant.” Before his capture, 
Marsili had spent his entire life being served by others. Servants dressed him, brought him water, cleaned his rooms, prepared his meals, and carried
out tasks so ordinary that he barely noticed them. Then, almost overnight, his world reversed completely. He became the one pouring drinks, carrying supplies, 
cleaning filth, obeying orders, and performing tasks he admits he would rather not describe aloud. “It was humiliating,” he says plainly,
“but humiliation was not the important part.” The pasha beat him sometimes for mistakes, sometimes for nothing at all except exhaustion or anger,
yet Marsili speaks of it with surprising calmness. “I have seen worse cruelty done with worse intention,” he says quietly. “And I have lived too long 
to lie about suffering just to make myself sound brave.”

What stayed with him most was not the pain but what he learned while becoming almost invisible inside the Ottoman camp. 
Servants, he explains, see the parts of power that diplomats and nobles never notice. They hear arguments between officers, learn which leaders ar
e feared or respected, watch soldiers prepare before dawn, and witness what powerful men reveal when they believe nobody important is listening. 
“Diplomats see thrones,” Marsili says. “Servants see reality.” Because he poured coffee and remained silent, people stopped noticing him entirely, 
and in that invisibility he discovered how much information powerful men reveal in front of those they consider beneath them. The old man leans forward
slightly, pale eyes fixed on yours. “If you are ever near powerful people,” he says softly, “be quiet. Be useful. Listen more than you speak. 
You will learn more in one hour than they will learn in a lifetime.”

[[Ask who bought him after the Pasha -> VI. The Brothers]]
[[Return to the objects on his desk -> Conversation]]

==================================================================

:: VI. The Brothers
“There came a day I was sold again,” the old man says quietly, staring somewhere beyond the room itself. “Twice a slave. That is a strange sentence to say aloud.”
After months serving in the pasha’s household, he was bought by two Bosnian brothers who traveled alongside the Ottoman armies as merchants,
buying and selling whatever soldiers needed during war. But unlike the men before them, these brothers already knew who Marsili was before they 
purchased him. They had drunk the coffee he prepared in the pasha’s camp and had become curious about the strange Italian who spoke in broken Turkish 
and answered questions no ordinary servant should have been able to answer. “Most men gave commands,” Marsili says. “These two asked questions instead.”
They wanted to know about Bologna, about its towers and paintings, about Christian customs and European cities they had never seen, and Marsili 
answered as best he could in imperfect Turkish while they laughed kindly at his mistakes rather than punishing them. “It mattered more than it should have,” 
he admits softly. “By then I had almost forgotten what ordinary kindness sounded like.”

Caterina asks whether he remembers their names, and for the first time the old man hesitates longer than usual. Eventually he shakes his head.
“No,” he says quietly. “And I am ashamed of that.” Memory, he explains, is cruel in its own way. It preserves fear and humiliation with perfect
clarity while sometimes erasing gentler things completely. The names of the two brothers disappeared over time even though he later wrote about them 
in his treatise on coffee. What he remembers instead is a single moment: coins changing hands one morning in the outer camp, the taller brother placing
a hand on his shoulder—not harshly, simply firmly—and telling him not to be afraid. Marsili admits he did not fully believe him then, because captivity
leaves little room for trust, but the brothers proved different from the others. They treated him as useful rather than invisible. He could read, write,
speak several languages, and prepare coffee properly, and because of that they relied on him openly instead of pretending he was less than human. 
“There is dignity in being needed honestly,” Marsili says. “It is a strange kind of freedom inside captivity.”

Years later, when he finally wrote his own work about coffee, he included them in its pages because he understood something important:
coffee itself had saved his life. Through the making of it he met the Bosnian brothers, and through them he survived long enough to one day return home. 
The old man looks down at the cup in his hand with a faint smile. “I owe a debt,” he says softly, “to a bean. And to two men whose names I forgot.” 
For the first time since beginning the story, he sounds genuinely regretful. “Kindness deserves memory,” he says quietly. “I should have written their names down.”

[[Ask how he finally escaped captivity -> VII. A Small Cup]]
[[Return to the objects on his desk -> Conversation]]

========================================================================

:: VII. A Small Cup
The old man gently pushes the tiny porcelain cup across the desk toward Caterina. “Drink,” he says. “You look as though I have handed you poison 
instead of coffee.” The cup feels surprisingly light in her hands, and the dark liquid inside smells bitter, smoky, and strangely distant, like warmth 
carried from another country entirely. She takes a careful sip and immediately pauses. The taste is sharp at first, almost unpleasant, yet underneath it 
lingers a hidden sweetness she did not expect. Marsili watches her reaction with obvious satisfaction. “There,” he says with a faint smile. “Now you have
done something your grandmother never did. Welcome to the eighteenth century.”

He explains that he first learned to make coffee while still in Ottoman captivity, preparing it inside military camps filled with smoke, 
mud, exhausted soldiers, and endless movement. The pasha gave him a charcoal brazier, a copper pot, and sacks of dark oily beans, turning 
him officially into a kahveci—a coffee-maker for the Ottoman army itself. As the army marched toward Vienna, Marsili spent his days roasting 
beans until they gleamed with oil, grinding them finer than flour, and learning the careful process required to make the drink correctly. 
“The foam was everything,” he says seriously. “The Turks believed coffee without foam was like a wedding without music.” Soon he was preparing cup 
after cup not only for soldiers but for officers, pashas, merchants, and eventually the Bosnian brothers as well, and while he served them he listened 
constantly. Soldiers told their coffee-maker things they would never tell commanders or wives, and Marsili quietly gathered information, observations, 
recipes, and stories while learning more about the drink itself from the writings of Husayn Efendi, the scholar he had met years earlier in Constantinople.

After finally regaining his freedom in 1685, Marsili carried those notes back to Europe and published one of the earliest books about 
coffee ever printed there, describing where it came from, how it was prepared, and what effects it had on the body. He glances toward the 
cup in Caterina’s hands with visible amusement. “Think about it,” he says. “A captive carried his captors’ drink back to Europe, and now here you 
are in Bologna drinking it as though it had always belonged here.” He leans back slowly, still smiling to himself. “I admit,” he says quietly,
“I am rather proud of that.”

[[Ask about the strange cannon sketches on the desk -> VIII. The Dangerous Pages]]

=================================================================================


:: VIII. The Dangerous Pages
The warmth disappears from the old man’s face almost instantly. He glances briefly toward the closed door behind you before speaking again, 
as though even now he is not entirely certain who might be listening. “There was another book,” he says quietly, “one I began writing during my captivity.
And it was far more dangerous than the one about coffee.” While serving inside the Ottoman camps, Marsili listened constantly while pretending not to exist.
He poured coffee for officers, merchants, commanders, and visiting officials, and because nobody noticed the servant holding the tray, nobody cared what he 
overheard. At night, after the camp had gone quiet, he secretly wrote everything down by candlelight stolen from the pasha’s own supplies. 
He recorded the structure of the Ottoman army, how regiments were organized and paid, where gunpowder was stored, how orders moved through the camp, 
where weaknesses existed, and how quickly messages traveled between commanders. He described the janissaries, the cavalry, the irregular soldiers who
fought for plunder, even the way the army buried its dead. “But above all,” he says, his pale eyes sharpening slightly, “I wrote about the cannons.”

He explains that the Ottoman cannons marching toward Vienna were unlike anything most Europeans had ever seen—massive weapons dragged by teams of oxen, 
built by generations of master gunmakers in Constantinople. Marsili carefully studied their dimensions, their firing methods, the order in which crews
loaded and operated them, and he drew detailed sketches of everything he could observe before hiding the pages inside bundles of laundry within his tent.
“Nobody in Christendom truly knew these things,” he says. “Ambassadors saw ceremonies. Spies saw fragments. But I lived inside the camp itself.” 
If the writings had been discovered, he knows exactly what would have happened. “They would not have killed me quickly,” he says calmly.
“They would have made an example of me in front of the entire camp.” For eight months he lived with that fear every day, checking constantly to make 
sure the hidden pages remained undiscovered, yet he continued writing anyway. Eventually those secret notes became the foundation of a military study
of the Ottoman Empire published years later after his death. Marsili gives a faint, tired smile at the thought. “A whole empire,” he says softly, 
“studied and recorded by a man officially employed only to serve coffee.”

[[Ask how he finally returned home -> IX. The Long Way Home]]


=================================================================================


:: IX. The Long Way Home
“In the spring of 1684,” the old man says, “my ransom was finally arranged, and after eight months inside the Ottoman camp I walked out a free man.” 
He pauses for a moment before continuing. “People always imagine freedom as something dramatic. They imagine running, weeping, falling to the ground in relief.
I imagined those things too.” But when the moment finally arrived, none of it happened. He simply walked past the final sentry, crossed an open field, and 
continued down a road toward the men waiting to receive him, feeling not joy but a strange emptiness he could not explain. “It felt,” he says quietly, 
“as though I had left something important behind in the camp.” When Caterina asks what it was, the old man gives her a surprised look. 
“The man I had been before captivity,” he answers after a long silence. “He never truly came out of that tent with me. The man who returned was someone 
else entirely.”

Caterina assumes he returned home to Bologna after that, but Marsili shakes his head immediately. Instead, he returned to war. Having lived inside the 
Ottoman camps, studied their armies, and secretly recorded everything he learned, he had become one of the few Christian officers in Europe who truly 
understood the empire from within. “My knowledge was worth more than a regiment,” he says. But there was something else driving him too: anger, restlessness, 
and a sense that he no longer knew how to live quietly. So he rejoined the Emperor’s forces, helping during the campaigns to retake Buda and later Belgrade,
using the knowledge he had gathered during captivity to understand Ottoman defenses and weaknesses. Years later, after more wars and negotiations,
he helped draw the new borders between empires following the Treaty of Karlowitz. By then he was no longer a prisoner or servant. He was a general of the 
Empire itself. The old man smiles faintly at the irony. “The slave who once poured coffee for soldiers ended his military life commanding them instead.”

For a moment the room falls quiet before Marsili suddenly changes the subject. He asks about Caterina’s brother, the same brother who told
her girls were not welcome inside the Institute. When she explains that he studies law and considers himself very clever, Marsili laughs softly.
“Good,” he says. “Then when you next see him, tell him you spent the afternoon drinking coffee with a count who survived slavery, studied the Ottoman 
Empire from inside its camps, and became a general afterward.” His pale eyes brighten with amusement. “Then ask whether he has done anything half as
interesting this week.”

[[Ask about the maps covering the walls -> X. The River, Drawn]]

====================================================================

:: X. The River, Drawn
Marsili gestures toward the enormous river chart covering half the wall behind him. “The border I helped draw after the Treaty of Karlowitz
followed the Danube for hundreds of miles,” he explains. “Most officers would have drawn the line, signed the papers, and gone home. I stayed for years.”
What began as military work slowly became obsession. Officially, he was there to measure territory for the Emperor, surveying rivers, forests, and frontier 
lands so two empires could agree where one ended and the other began. But Marsili could never look at a landscape without wanting to understand everything 
inside it. So while traveling the Danube by boat with assistants, instruments, and stacks of paper, he began studying the river itself in exhausting detail.
He measured its width, depth, and currents, climbed its banks to copy Roman inscriptions, mapped ruined fortresses, catalogued minerals from nearby rocks,
and dragged nets through the water to sketch unfamiliar fish species no one had properly documented before. He even drew birds’ eggs because, as he
explains with complete seriousness, “If you do not understand the beginning of a thing, you do not truly understand the thing itself.”

Eventually all of those notes, sketches, maps, measurements, and observations became his greatest work: *Danubius Pannonico-Mysicus*,
a massive six-volume study of the Danube published years later with elaborate engravings made by some of Europe’s finest artists. With visible effort, 
Marsili pulls one enormous leather-bound volume from a nearby shelf and places it carefully on the desk between you. When he opens it, the pages 
reveal fish, birds, plants, ruins, and detailed river maps drawn with astonishing precision. “An entire river between two covers,” he says quietly,
almost proud despite himself. What had started as the field notes of a military officer eventually became something far larger—part science, part exploration,
part history, and part obsession. Marsili runs a hand gently across the page before looking back at you with faint amusement.
“I was supposed to draw a border,” he says. “Instead I accidentally documented an entire world.”

[[Ask about the strange glass tube on the desk -> XI. The Ampoule]]
[[Ask about the sea maps nearby -> XII. The Wet World]]

=========================================================================

:: XI. The Ampoule
“Come closer,” the old man says softly, lifting the slender glass tube from its velvet cloth with surprising care, as though it were something 
fragile enough to bruise. Up close, the instrument seems almost unimpressive: a narrow weighted tube with faint markings along the side and a small 
stopper at the top. Marsili notices your uncertainty immediately and smiles. “Exactly,” he says. “The best instruments rarely look impressive.” 
He lowers the tube gently into one of the cloudy jars on his desk, where it floats upright in the water. As the surface settles against the markings,
he explains that the instrument measures density, salinity, and even temperature depending on how it is used. Saltier water causes it to float differently
than fresh water, allowing him to compare one body of water against another using actual measurements instead of guesses or stories. “That,” he says quietly, 
“was the important part. Numbers. Dates. Places. Not legends. Not opinions.” Using early versions of this simple device, he began recording measurements
in the Bosporus, the Aegean Sea, the Sea of Marmara, and later throughout the Mediterranean, carefully documenting how different waters behaved and moved. 
To Marsili, every measurement became part of a larger language the sea was speaking, one nobody had truly tried to record before.

He places the ampoule carefully back onto the velvet cloth and rests his hand beside it for a moment. Over the years, he explains, 
other scientists would create better instruments, explore deeper waters, and eventually map the ocean floor itself, but he takes quiet satisfaction in
knowing that some of the very first true oceanographic measurements began with this simple glass tube and a curious young man asking questions beside the Bosporus.
“The sea hides its truths beneath the surface,” he says. “Most people are content simply to look at it. I wanted to interrogate it.” For the first time
since beginning the story, Caterina notices genuine pride in his voice—not pride in titles or military victories, but in discovery itself. Marsili gives 
the instrument one final glance before looking back toward you with faint amusement. “A strange thing to dedicate your life to,” he admits. 
“But I have always trusted questions more than answers.”

[[Ask about the maps of the sea nearby -> XII. The Wet World]]
[[Ask what he believes lies beneath the ocean -> XIII. No Monsters]]

====================================================================================

:: XII. The Wet World
“In 1703,” the old man says, “I lost a fortress called Breisach.” He says the name without emphasis, as though it belongs to someone else’s life rather
than his own. “You will not have heard of it, and that is fine. I surrendered it, was court-martialled, demoted, stripped of my property, and disgraced.” 
He pauses, then adds something unexpected. “And it was the best thing that ever happened to me.” Caterina frowns. “How can disgrace be the best thing?”
“Because it ended usefulness,” he replies simply. “For twenty-two years I had been a soldier with orders, duties, and a place in the world. 
After Breisach, I had none of that anymore. I had nothing left that anyone required from me. And so, for the first time since childhood, 
I had only curiosity.” What followed was not retirement but wandering: Switzerland, Milan, Versailles where even a disgraced general was still treated 
as an interesting object, and eventually the coast of Provence at Cassis, where he returned again to the sea he had first studied decades earlier.
There, he began again with the same simple tools: the ampoule, weighted lines to feel the seafloor, dredging equipment that pulled up
fragments of a world no one had ever properly examined. “When you dredge,” he says quietly, “you bring up things you did not know existed.”
Among those things were corals—structures most scholars of his time insisted were plants. Marsili studied them carefully under magnification and came to
a different conclusion: they were animals, living in vast colonies and building stone-like structures over time. The idea was mocked at first, but he was right,
even if it took half a century for others to accept it.
From Provence he mapped the seabed as systematically as he had once mapped military fortresses, charting slopes, depths, sediments, and 
sudden underwater drops along the coast. In doing so, he unknowingly created one of the earliest systematic attempts to describe the physical structure
of the sea itself. This work became *Histoire physique de la mer*, published in Amsterdam in 1725, the first comprehensive study of its kind. Marsili 
gives a small, almost amused shrug as he finishes the thought. “Some people now call me a founder of oceanography,” he says. “It is an ugly word, but
I have learned that important words often are.”

[[Ask what he believes lies beneath the ocean -> XIII. No Monsters]]


=======================================================================


:: XIII. No Monsters
The old man leans forward across the desk, and for the first time all afternoon there is a sharpness in his voice that was not there before, as though
something long settled in him has been stirred back into motion by the late October light falling through the window. “This,” he says, “is the idea I am 
most proud of—and the one men mocked me for most.” He explains that in his time the deep ocean is still imagined as a separate world full of serpents,
monsters, and endless darkness. Maps leave blank spaces beneath the sea or fill them with creatures invented by men who have never truly explored it.
Sailors repeat stories, scholars repeat older stories, and everyone accepts that beneath the waves lies something magical and unknowable. Marsili shakes
his head slowly. “But I had looked.” For years he lowered instruments into the sea, measured depths, dredged the seabed, and studied what came back up from below.
Again and again he found the same thing: sand, rocks, slopes, valleys, ridges—the same geography that exists on land, only hidden underwater. “The continents do
not stop at the shore,” he says quietly. “They continue beneath the sea.” Caterina thinks about this for a moment before admitting that the idea sounds
strangely obvious once spoken aloud. The old man laughs immediately, delighted by the answer. “Exactly. For centuries men preferred monsters simply because
nobody bothered to look properly.”
He grows quieter then, almost thoughtful. One day, he says, future explorers will chart the ocean floor completely, naming underwater mountains and 
valleys just as people map countries and rivers on land. Perhaps somewhere on those future maps there will be a small note remembering the first man who 
realized the sea floor was simply another landscape waiting to be understood. Marsili looks toward the fading window light before speaking again, softer now.
“If that day comes,” he says, “read it for me.”

[[Ask about the Institute and this room -> XIV. The Gift]]

==============================================================

:: XIV. The Gift
The study glows with late-afternoon light as Marsili gestures around the room and explains that after his disgrace at Breisach he donated everything he had 
collected — books, instruments, fossils, maps, manuscripts, and eventually even the palazzo itself — so Bologna could create a place where young people might
study the world through observation instead of repeating old books. From that idea came the Istituto delle Scienze, devoted to experiment, curiosity,
and discovery. “The point is not the glass cases,” he says softly. “The point is to open them.” He tells Caterina that honours from Paris and London mattered 
less to him than this house and the people who might one day learn inside it. Then he rises slowly, takes her hand, and asks her to return someday and remember 
him when she does. At the doorway she looks back once more and sees him already bent again over his maps beside the porcelain coffee cup. She closes the door
gently behind her and walks out into the cool evening streets of Bologna knowing she will remember this conversation for the rest of her life.
